    "summary": "The Kurdish people, the world's largest ethnic group without their own state with an estimated 25–35 million people distributed across Turkey, Iraq, Iran, and Syria, pursued various forms of political and armed struggle for cultural recognition and autonomy throughout the twentieth century. The most sustained armed insurgency was that of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK) in Turkey, which launched guerrilla warfare against the Turkish state in 1984 under the leadership of Abdullah Öcalan, seeking initially an independent Kurdish state and later broader cultural and political rights.\n\nThe PKK conflict in Turkey had by 2000 claimed over 40,000 lives, mostly in the southeast of the country, and involved widespread human rights abuses by both the PKK and Turkish security forces. Hundreds of Kurdish villages were forcibly evacuated and destroyed. Öcalan was captured in Kenya in 1999 and sentenced to death, later commuted to life imprisonment. In Iraq, Kurdish populations in the north had suffered brutal repression under Saddam Hussein, including the Anfal genocide campaign of 1986–1989 in which chemical weapons were used against Kurdish civilians. The Gulf War's aftermath created a de facto Kurdish autonomous zone in northern Iraq protected by a US-enforced no-fly zone, which evolved into the Kurdistan Regional Government.",
